@Marshall Walthew 
Good luck charm indeed. Wiki tells me that the Flyers’ record was 100 W, 29L, and 5T when that song was played or sung live by her before games. A special one was at the Spectrum at game 6 of the Stanley Cup Finals against the Bruins in 1974. It is said that Bobby Orr and Phil Esposito tried to jinx that by shaking her hand afterwards, but the Flyers still won. For many years, this was also played during the 7th inning stretch at Yankee Stadium ( our Warsaw  friend may not know about that). Here’s a clip of the 1974 surprise live appearance , including the famous handshakes:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/bddxjzch" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/bddxjzch</a>

@Steve L 

I think I understand what you are saying, and if so, that'd be the a great example of timidity of the NYT, in the face of truth vs lies.

We have one major news outlet and several spinoffs that are essentially nothing but lies.  This has rent the country in two, and will ultimately be the cause of its demise, probably sooner rather than later.

@J-J Cote 

It's only obvious if you know it. Had I not accompanied my parents on trips to garden centers almost 30 years ago, I would never have learned the word (which is very similar in Polish - azalia. It sounds to us Poles pretty much as AZALEA does to you).

I can well understand why somebody would be stumped by that crossing.

@MExpat 

Eh, but there’s fundamentally no such thing as prescriptive linguistics, unless we’re talking about Esperanto — any prescriptive account of a real language consists of no more than documenting a descriptive snapshot of that language’s usage from a particular time and place (or some composite thereof) and then calling that “correct”.

Anyhoo: I definitely wanted to”economical” as the answer for 13A, but I’d disagree that the clue given was *wrong*, for the simple reason that it’s a *clue* (as opposed to a definition), and worked just fine in that capacity.

@CCNY 

Here's a nasty little secret: electronic scanners have been able to detect marks made by other writing instruments for years.  Yet schools still keep buying #2 pencils.

On the other hand, much standardized testing is now moving towards online administration, so maybe those pencils will go the way of the slide rule soon.

@Darcey O’D 
The norm for pencils is HB. No-one calls it that, it's just a pencil.
There are B pencils, 1-5 I think, which get softer and softer. H pencils 1-5 which get harder and harder. Only really used by sketchers.

@Andrzej 

Before I realized I was going to need PANTSED, I thought the 32A clue, [Open for drinks], clued "tab".  When you order a round of drinks for the first time at a bar, don't you open one of those?  (Of course, TAP is a verb here, and that's what you need, and "tab" isn't used as a verb.)

(He asks naively, since he doesn't go to bars.)

@Steve 

Any SNL clue = instant Google for me. Duh.

However, today I would have probably got the clue with one or two crosses, too.

@Petrol 

Just stuff you don't know.  I thought every one of them was fine and quite normal, and I'd bet so did many others.

It may come down to whether you're an expat or a native of France, and if you're the former, for how long.

@Ms. Billie M. Spaight 

It is the first game I play in the morning so it is, quite literally, my "eye opener".  

Would love to see your results.  You can use the Share Your Results button to copy your board and paste it into a comment here.

@Pani Korunova 

Knowing Spanish already, I can figure out 90% of written Portuguese.  However, that doesn't translate to understanding the spoken language, which doesn't sound anything like Spanish.

When I was in Portugal last summer, I realized Portuguese is the language that looks like Spanish and sounds like Russian.

@Tom 

When I went to school in RI there was a large French-speaking community in Woonsocket.

Don't know whether it's still that way.

@Steve L 

Sh sounds, sure, but the accent and intonation are completely different.

I don't speak Russian btw. I probably know more Russian words than you do, but not many more. I can also read most - but not all - of the Cyrillic alphabet. Kids born in 1980 - like me - were the first generation to be taught English rather than Russian at school (but due to my parents' efforts I spoke better English than my school teacher by the 5th grade, when foreign language lessons started).

